text: Just finished reading the sequel to Stephen King's universally acclaimed horror masterpiece, The Shinning, entitled Doctor Sleep. The story primarily occurs many years after the first novel, with Dan working at a hospice in rural New Hampshire, where he uses the remnants of his shining ability to ease the suffering of the dying at the moment of death. He meets a young girl named Abra Stone, who also has the shining. Abra is in mortal danger from a group of quasi-immortals called the True Knot, who live off the 'steam' that children with the shining produce when they are slowly tortured to death. Dan risks everything, to protect Abra from the murderous paranormals, just as s young black cook at the Overlook Hotel once risked everything to save him.  As a sequel, Doctor Sleep starts off promising. Early on, Dan winds up exactly where his father started in The Shinning: drunk, and hitting his rock bottom, and wanting desperately to find a good place to escape his own personal demons. Reading about Dan falling into the same fate as Jack Torrance, the exact fate I had hoped he'd avoid, was an extremely painful experience, but also a welcome one. It nearly moved me to tears, and proved to me that I still cared about the little boy I met years ago reading the first novel, even if I didn't care to much for anyone else in Doctor Sleep.   If the quality of a piece of literature is judged solely by the extent it makes you emotional, then the early chapters were the best. As Doctor Sleep got further and further away from the plot of The Shinning, I cared less and less. I think Stephen King tried hard to make me love Abra the same way I loved Dan, but I just couldn't. She was a smart and funny character, and her relationship with Dan was cute, but everything was far to easy for her. It is a characters struggle, and the fear of what might happen to them, I think, that causes people to care about fictional characters as though they were real. Abra's shinning was so powerful that I never once felt she was in any real danger. The almost comical villains with their silly names didn't exactly help make things suspenseful. I wanted to truly fear them, but there was nothing frightening about them. I wanted more along the lines of Horace Derwent or the dead woman from Room 217, and what I got was the Wicked Witch of the West. Hat and all. I remember, even though I was older when I first read it, The Shinning was genuinely scary at times, reading it alone in the dark with a flashlight. Especially with the loud BANG! caused by people bursting through my bedroom door at random intervals. I did not have the same experience with this novel. It is very different from the Shinning, not only in terms of the plot of the story, but also how it was written, even though both were obviously written by the same man.   At no point does Doctor Sleep ever come close to approaching anything I would call "horror." To use movie terms, Doctor Sleep the book felt more like a direct to DVD successor to The Shining then a true sequel. By the end, Doctor Sleep had plenty of faults, but it was still a good book, because at no point did it actually bore me, and worth the read. It just wasn't anywhere near as good as The Shinning.

text: I hope this movie can finally bridge the gap in my mind between King's original book and Kubrick's film adaptation of The Shining. Both were amazing in their own right but incompatible with each other. The director has both the blessing of King himself and the Kubrick estate so I trust that he can navigate both stories to make something truly new and great. Hill House, Oculus, and Gerald's Game are all fantastic so I'm cautiously interested in how Mike Flanagan is going to approach this.

text: So far this looks promising, It seems the filmmakers did a better job than Kubrick on this film. I'm sorry but after having read both books, Kubrick ruined the story. Jack was a loving father with his own demons who tried to fight against the hotels power and killed himself to protect his son Wendy was a strong willed woman who took no shit from anyone, even jack. She was willing to divorce Jack for their son if need be, carrying a frightening phobia of becoming just like her mother.  Halloran never died until at least doctor sleep while Danny is an alcoholic but he never knew. However, he is present during most of Danny's young life before he dies.  However, this film seems very impressive and loyal to the book, I can't wait to see the movie

text: I'm interested to watch, but I'm going to intentionally go in with no expectations, so as not to be disappointed. I don't want to try to compare the original Shining, to its sequel-ish thing. Nothing will ever compare to Kubrick's masterpiece, in my opinion. That's probably my all time favorite horror movie, if I had to choose just one, which is really difficult. Stephen King did NOT care for Kubrick's adaptation of The Shining, and there is one thing I can agree with him on... which is the fact that, he didn't like that Mr. Torrence (Jack Nicholson) seemed "off" or kinda crazy, from the very beginning. King said that it was supposed to be a slow descent into madness, by a seemingly "normal" individual. I've not read The Shining, but it's on my to do list. It just so happens, that I share the same opinion as King. I remember thinking about it once and then later, I read an article about why he didn't like Kubrick's adaptation of his novel and that was one of the reasons I recall. I remember thinking, "what?! So the book is actually written, how I thought it should've been in the movie? I feel cheated!" I can't recall if Kubrick wanted it that way, or if Jack Nicholson just overplayed the character. I want to say it's the latter, according to King. I personally loved his performance and I don't think the movie would be, what it is, without him. However, I do wish that he would've acted less like he had underlying mental issues, from the very beginning. Anyways, sorry, went off on a tangent there. Hope the movie is decent. The end.

text: I saw The Shining when I was 8.  It messed me up for a few years.  I would not go to the bathroom without propping open the door and having the shower curtain pulled if I was home alone, because of the bathtub scene.  Or I would hold the door open with one leg while balancing on the other while trying to piss.  This went on until I was 12.  I saw the movie again on cable TV, and it wasn't as scary as I remembered from seeing it years earlier at the drive in.  After that I was okay.  But man...I still get the goosebumps when I hear the music.
